          "id": "medquad-chunk-970bde8f0fdbd4ca",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Atherosclerosis ?",
          "content": "Atherosclerosis is a condition that often goes unnoticed until it has caused significant narrowing or complete blockage of an artery. This means that many people may not be aware they have this disease until they face a serious health crisis, such as a heart attack or stroke. However, some individuals may experience signs and symptoms, which can vary depending on which arteries are affected in the body.\nLet's explore the different types of arteries and the symptoms associated with atherosclerosis in each case:\n**Coronary Arteries**\nThe coronary arteries are responsible for delivering oxygen-rich blood to the heart muscle. When plaque builds up in these arteries, it can lead to a condition known as coronary heart disease (CHD). One of the most common symptoms of CHD is angina, which is a type of chest pain or discomfort. Angina can feel like a heavy pressure or squeezing sensation in the chest, and it may also be felt in the shoulders, arms, neck, jaw, or back. Some people describe angina pain as similar to indigestion. This discomfort often worsens during physical activity and tends to improve with rest. Emotional stress can also trigger angina symptoms.\nIn addition to angina, individuals with CHD may experience shortness of breath, which is a feeling of not being able to get enough air, and arrhythmias, which are irregular heartbeats that can feel like a fluttering or racing in the chest.\nPlaque can also accumulate in the smaller arteries of the heart, leading to a condition called coronary microvascular disease (MVD). Symptoms of coronary MVD can include angina, shortness of breath, fatigue, sleep problems, and a general lack of energy.\n**Carotid Arteries**\nThe carotid arteries are crucial as they supply oxygen-rich blood to the brain. If plaque builds up in these arteries, it can lead to carotid artery disease, which increases the risk of stroke. Symptoms that may indicate a stroke include sudden weakness or numbness, particularly on one side of the body, confusion, difficulty speaking or understanding speech, vision problems in one or both eyes, and issues with balance or coordination. Other symptoms may include dizziness, trouble walking, and even loss of consciousness. A sudden and severe headache can also be a warning sign of a stroke.\n**Peripheral Arteries**\nAtherosclerosis can also affect the peripheral arteries, which supply blood to the legs, arms, and pelvis. When plaque builds up in these arteries, it can lead to peripheral artery disease. Symptoms of this condition may include numbness, pain, and in some cases, serious infections in the affected areas. Individuals may notice pain in their legs or arms, especially during physical activities such as walking or climbing stairs.\n**Renal Arteries**\nThe renal arteries are responsible for supplying oxygen-rich blood to the kidneys. If plaque accumulates in these arteries, it can lead to chronic kidney disease over time. Early stages of kidney disease often do not present any noticeable signs or symptoms, which can make it difficult to detect. However, as the disease progresses, individuals may experience fatigue, changes in urination patterns (either more frequent or less frequent), loss of appetite, nausea, swelling in the hands or feet, itchiness or numbness, and difficulty concentrating.\nUnderstanding the symptoms associated with atherosclerosis is essential for early detection and management of the condition. If you or someone you know experiences any of these symptoms, it is important to seek medical attention promptly to prevent serious health complications.\nContext recap: Atherosclerosis is a condition that often goes unnoticed until it has caused significant narrowing or complete blockage of an artery. This means that many people may not be aware they have this disease until they face a serious health crisis, such as a heart attack or stroke. However, some individuals may experience signs and symptoms, which can vary depending on which arteries are affected in the body. Let's explore the different types of arteries and the symptoms associated with atherosclerosis in each case:\n**Coronary Arteries**\nThe coronary arteries are responsible for delivering oxygen-rich blood to the heart muscle.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Atherosclerosis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Cardiology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Atherosclerosis is a condition that often goes unnoticed until it has caused significant narrowing or complete blockage of an artery. This means that many people may not be aware they have this disease until they face a serious health crisis, such as a heart attack or stroke. However, some individuals may experience signs and symptoms, which can vary depending on which arteries are affected in the body. Let's explore the different types of arteries and the symptoms associated with atherosclerosis in each case:\n**Coronary Arteries**\nThe coronary arteries are responsible for delivering oxygen-rich blood to the heart muscle.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Atherosclerosis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Cardiology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
          "kind": "concept"
