          "id": "medquad-chunk-66b6fbaf2ff3379d",
          "title": "Who is at risk for Kawasaki Disease? ?",
          "content": "Kawasaki disease is a condition that can impact children from various backgrounds, regardless of their race or gender. It is important to note that this disease is most frequently diagnosed in children who are of Asian and Pacific Island descent. Research shows that boys are more likely to develop Kawasaki disease compared to girls, which highlights a gender difference in its occurrence. The majority of cases are found in young children, particularly those under the age of 5. As children grow older, especially those over the age of 8, the likelihood of developing Kawasaki disease significantly decreases, making it quite rare in this older age group. Recognizing these risk factors is crucial for parents and healthcare providers, as it can lead to earlier detection and more effective treatment of the disease, ultimately improving health outcomes for affected children.\nContext recap: Kawasaki disease is a condition that can impact children from various backgrounds, regardless of their race or gender. It is important to note that this disease is most frequently diagnosed in children who are of Asian and Pacific Island descent. Research shows that boys are more likely to develop Kawasaki disease compared to girls, which highlights a gender difference in its occurrence. The majority of cases are found in young children, particularly those under the age of 5.\nWhy this matters: Who is at risk for Kawasaki Disease? ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Cardiology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Kawasaki disease is a condition that can impact children from various backgrounds, regardless of their race or gender. It is important to note that this disease is most frequently diagnosed in children who are of Asian and Pacific Island descent. Research shows that boys are more likely to develop Kawasaki disease compared to girls, which highlights a gender difference in its occurrence. The majority of cases are found in young children, particularly those under the age of 5.\nWhy this matters: Who is at risk for Kawasaki Disease? ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Cardiology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Kawasaki disease is a condition that can impact children from various backgrounds, regardless of their race or gender. It is important to note that this disease is most frequently diagnosed in children who are of Asian and Pacific Island descent. Research shows that boys are more likely to develop Kawasaki disease compared to girls, which highlights a gender difference in its occurrence. The majority of cases are found in young children, particularly those under the age of 5.\nWhy this matters: Who is at risk for Kawasaki Disease? ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Cardiology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
