          "id": "medquad-chunk-74fca108512434aa",
          "title": "What are the symptoms of Kawasaki Disease ?",
          "content": "Kawasaki disease is a serious condition that can affect children, and it is important to recognize its symptoms early for proper treatment. During the early stage of the disease, known as the acute phase, one of the most noticeable symptoms is a high fever. This fever lasts for more than 5 days and does not go down even with common medications used to reduce fever in children.\nIn addition to the fever, there are several other classic signs that can help identify Kawasaki disease. These include:\n- **Swollen lymph nodes**: You may notice that the lymph nodes in your child's neck are swollen, which can indicate that their body is fighting an infection.\n- **Rash**: A rash may develop on the mid-section of the body and in the genital area, which can vary in appearance.\n- **Red, dry, cracked lips**: Your child might have lips that look very red and dry, and their tongue may also appear red and swollen.\n- **Swollen hands and feet**: The palms of the hands and the soles of the feet may become red and swollen, which can be uncomfortable for your child.\n- **Redness in the eyes**: You might notice that the whites of your child's eyes are red, which is another sign of Kawasaki disease.\nAlong with these major symptoms, children with Kawasaki disease may also feel irritable and may complain of a sore throat. They might experience joint pain, diarrhea, vomiting, and stomach pain during this acute phase.\nIt is also important to note that within 2 to 3 weeks after the symptoms first appear, some children may experience peeling skin on their fingers and toes. This peeling can happen in large sheets and is another sign that the body is reacting to the disease.\nRecognizing these symptoms early is crucial, as timely medical intervention can help manage the condition effectively and reduce the risk of complications. If you notice any of these signs in your child, it is important to seek medical advice promptly.\nContext recap: Kawasaki disease is a serious condition that can affect children, and it is important to recognize its symptoms early for proper treatment. During the early stage of the disease, known as the acute phase, one of the most noticeable symptoms is a high fever. This fever lasts for more than 5 days and does not go down even with common medications used to reduce fever in children. In addition to the fever, there are several other classic signs that can help identify Kawasaki disease.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Kawasaki Disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Cardiology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Kawasaki disease is a serious condition that can affect children, and it is important to recognize its symptoms early for proper treatment. During the early stage of the disease, known as the acute phase, one of the most noticeable symptoms is a high fever. This fever lasts for more than 5 days and does not go down even with common medications used to reduce fever in children. In addition to the fever, there are several other classic signs that can help identify Kawasaki disease.\nWhy this matters: What are the symptoms of Kawasaki Disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Cardiology (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.",
